.SH EXAMPLES
The following example uses program \fBplctest\fR to download and execute \fBhello.nvm\fR. The applets executes, sends an ARPC message and and exits, returning to the bootloader. Observe that the console prompt appears after execution because this applet terminates.
.PP
   # plctest hello.nvm 
   eth1 00:B0:52:00:00:01 Writing hello.nvm (0) (00210000:5104)
   eth1 00:B0:52:00:00:01 Written
   eth1 00:B0:52:00:00:01 Starting Software (00210004)
   eth1 00:B0:52:00:00:01 Started
   *** Hello World!!! ***
   #
.PP
The next example downloads and executes three \fBhello.nvm\fR applets. Each applet executes in turn and returns to the bootloader, allowing the next applet to execute. This is the easiest way to create an applet chain. Observe that the console prompt appears after execution because this applet terminates.
.PP
   # plctest hello.nvm hello.nvm hello.nvm
   eth1 00:B0:52:00:00:01 Writing hello.nvm (0) (00210000:5104)
   eth1 00:B0:52:00:00:01 Written
   eth1 00:B0:52:00:00:01 Starting Software (00210004)
   eth1 00:B0:52:00:00:01 Started
   *** Hello World!!! ***
   eth1 00:B0:52:00:00:01 Writing hello.nvm (0) (00210000:5104)
   eth1 00:B0:52:00:00:01 Written
   eth1 00:B0:52:00:00:01 Starting Software (00210004)
   eth1 00:B0:52:00:00:01 Started
   *** Hello World!!! ***
   eth1 00:B0:52:00:00:01 Writing hello.nvm (0) (00210000:5104)
   eth1 00:B0:52:00:00:01 Written
   eth1 00:B0:52:00:00:01 Starting Software (00210004)
   eth1 00:B0:52:00:00:01 Started
   *** Hello World!!! ***
   #
.PP
The next example does the same thing but option \fB-q\fR is used to suppress progress information. Observe that the console prompt appears after execution because this applet terminates.
.PP
   # plctest -q hello.nvm hello.nvm hello.nvm
   *** Hello World!!! ***
   *** Hello World!!! ***
   *** Hello World!!! ***
   #
